# Save the Cat!
= (A highly granular beat sheet designed for pacing and genre satisfaction.) Goal: To ensure the narrative hits specific emotional beats at predictable time stamps to maintain audience engagement and satisfy genre tropes.

## Opening Image
= A single, visual snapshot of the protagonist's flawed "before" life. Sets the tone.

## Theme Stated
= A character (often a mentor) explicitly tells the protagonist what they need to learn or realize.

## Setup
= The normal world is established, showing supporting characters and setting up initial conflicts.

## Inciting Incident (Catalyst)
= The inciting event that kicks off the story and demands action.

## Debate
= The protagonist resists the call or struggles with the decision to engage fully in the conflict.

## Break into Two
= The point of commitment. The hero leaves home/the known world for the main adventure.

## B Story Introduced
= Introduces the emotional thread (often a romantic interest or mentor relationship) that will teach the protagonist how to grow.

## Fun and Games
= The "promise of the premise." A series of fun, escalating scenes showing the character in their new world before the real trouble starts.

## Midpoint
= A false victory or a massive defeat. Stakes are raised; momentum is irreversible.

## Bad Guys Close In
= The external and internal pressures mount. Failure begins to loom large.

## All Is Lost
= The emotional low point. Everything the protagonist has built falls apart, forcing them to confront their biggest flaw/fear.

## Dark Night of the Soul
= A moment of quiet despair and reflection where the character finally realizes the truth they needed to learn (the thematic realization).

## Break Into Three / Climax
= The hero uses their newfound knowledge (from the Dark Night) in a final, desperate attempt to save the day.

## Final Image
= A visual mirror of the Opening Image, showing how the protagonist has fundamentally changed and improved.
